That’s a fact that is important in understanding North Korea, how the Kim family became rulers and what is still driving (mostly out of fear) the distinct authoritarian behaviors of the country. This is a book that you’d want to read, not just in mid-2017, but throughout the years to understand a country that no one has figured out.

Most people outside of North Korea do not know about the life of the An family. From an early age, the An siblings have traveled all over the world — mainly in Asia and Europe — and how at an early age they followed the commands of their father, a diplomatic and elite businessman and who always was willing to ask the high-ups at the upper levels of North Korea to allow them to travel since they were considered both symbols of the ruling family and state. They also have variously dealt with or spoke to diplomats and spies all over the world. In 2010, they were on their way home from high school in Paris, but took a detour to stop in South Korea. The An family chose to remain in South Korea to start this new life. That’s how important it is to first understand what the An family is about.
